                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Manuscript in hiragana-majiri with illustrations of acupuncture
                            points and of various conditions of the eye with an explanation of the
                            diseases this indicated. The manuscript was copied in
                            <date>1816</date>.</summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_28">

                            <title>
                                <title type="original" xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">清眼流目医書</title>
                                <title type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn" source="IANA">Seiganryū
                                    mokuisho</title>
                                <title type="standard" xml:lang="en" source="IANA">Seiganryu-school
                                    Ophthalmology Text</title>
                                <note><p>English translation given by A Rose</p></note>
                            </title>

                            <colophon><locus/>文化十三歳丙子八月吉旦／松浦玄駿 <note><p>書写奥書 | Colophon written by
                                        the copyist</p></note>
                            </colophon>

                            <filiation><p>No manuscript bearing this title is recorded, though Kyōto
                                    University possesses a copy of <title xml:lang="ja-Latn"
                                        source="IANA">Seiganryū ganka hiden</title>
                                    <title xml:lang="ja" source="IANA">清眼流眼科秘</title>.
                                </p></filiation>

                            <note><p>The Seiganryū school of ophtalmology, usually known as the
                                    Majumaryū, was founded by <persName>Majima Seigan</persName>
                                    <persName xml:lang="ja" source="IANA"/>
                                    (died.<date>1379</date>), who was the first abbot of the Iōzan
                                    Yakushiji temple in Owari province following its refoundation;
                                    every subsequent abbot was a practising ophthalmologist and the
                                    tradition has survived into the twentieth century. This was a
                                    secret tradition, communicated orally and in manuscript
                                    form.</p></note>
                        </msItem>
                    </msContents>

